<h1>1.2. Save for a Rainy Day</h1>

<p>Imagine this scenario: your car insurance is due every 6 months for $450. The month rolls around, and you find that you're suddenly tight because you weren't anticipating the expense. Now the rest of the month is stressful and you have to cut back in other areas.</p>

<p>With rule 2, it looks completely different. Now, you split that cost over 6 months (the frequency of the payment). $450 divided by 6 is $75, so every month you budget $75 in the Car Insurance <a href="{{ path('tutorials_glossary') }}#category">category</a>.</p>

<p>That doesn't mean you spend that $75. It simply means that $75 is allocated towards car insurance every month. Recall in <a href="{{ path('tutorials_1_1') }}">chapter 1.1</a> how the amount not spent in a category will simply carry over to the next month. So, if you put $75 in Car Insurance in January and do not touch it, when February comes you will see the balance of that category is $75, but the budget is 0, because you did not budget anything to it yet in February. Once you budget your $75, your balance will then be $150.</p>

