<p>The <a href="{{ path('tutorials_glossary') }}#outflow">outflow</a> is $450.00, since that is what we spend on the insurance. Since there was exactly $450.00 lying around in our category, the balance goes down to $0.00 when the insurance is paid for.</p>

<p>With rule 2, the expense is paid without you barely noticing. Because of <a href="{{ path('tutorials_1_1') }}">rule 1</a>, you didn't simply look at your growing checking account balance and conclude you could splurge: you knew exactly what you could spend in each category at every given moment. The Car Insurance category simply sat there growing for 6 months, until you could just pay the bill without thinking twice about it or feeling even a slight bit of discomfort. It was sitting there ready to be used, so the stress of covering that bill has vanished.</p>

<p>But it doesn't only have to be used for predictable periodic expenses. Let's say you have a Home Maintenance category for those unexpected expenses that pop up from time-to-time. You budget $50 in that category every month, and pretty soon you have a healthy category balance of $1,000. Pretty soon you find your roof is leaking and needs repaired. The contractor comes out and quotes $500 for the work. YOu have no problem paying it immediately because you already had more than enough set aside to cover just such an occasion. YOu pay the $500, your roof gets fixed, and your Home Maintenance category is still looking healthy at $500 left over. That was almost too simple!</p>

<p>It will take a while to deduce exactly what you spend in each category on average, but once you figure out a good number for you, such expenses will simply go unnoticed, while before they would have caused massive stress and anxiety.</p>

<p>Other possible rainy day funds might include:</p>

<ul>
<li>Life insurance</li>
<li>Vacations</li>
<li>Medical expenses</li>
<li>Property taxes</li>
<li>Christmas, birthdays or other special events</li>
<li>Vet bills</li>
<li>College tuition</li>
</ul>

<p>It's all about planning. Once you <a href="{{ path('tutorials_1_1') }}">give every dollar a job</a>, and you save some of those dollars for a rainy day, your budget will almost seem to take care of itself. Avoiding the blow of these unexpected expenses will enable you to gradually increase your savings in other areas, and pretty soon financial anxiety will be a thing of the past.</p>

<h2>Rule 2 in Budget Banana</h2>

<p>Category balances automatically carry over to the next month. If you have $75 left over in Groceries, it will be reflected in your category balance for next month.</p>

<p>It is reflected in the formula to calculate the balance, which is:</p>

<p><pre>balance =
    positive category balance from last month
    + budgeted in category this month
    - outflows from category this month</pre></p>

<p>So if you have a balance of $75 from your Groceries category from last month, you budget $300 into Groceries this month, and have an outflow totaling $250, the balance will be:</p>

<p><pre>    $75 balance from last month
    + $300 budgeted this month
    - $250 outflow this month
    = $125 balance</pre></p>

<p>Notice how only positive balances carry over. The reason for this will be explained in <a href="{{ path('tutorials_1_3') }}">chapter 1.3</a>.</p>

